The paper deals with the point-location problem in high-dimensional space, which is a fundamental problem in computational geometry and data structures. The use of linear decision trees and generalized comparison queries suggests that the paper belongs to the computational geometry (cs.CG) and data structures (cs.DS) sub-categories. The analysis also involves margin-based inference dimension analysis, which is a technique commonly used in machine learning and information theory, indicating a possible connection to the information theory (cs.IT) sub-category. Finally, the paper uses compactness arguments, which are often used in complexity theory and circuit complexity, suggesting a possible connection to the computational complexity (cs.CC) sub-category.
